III.——ON THE Goon MAN: A PYTHAGOREAN SENTENCE

THE upright man and wise—Apollo, when in- voked,1 could searce find one such amongst all the thousands of mankind—sits in judgment on himself and searehes out his whole self to a hair's breadth. What the great think, or what the fickle opinion of the empty-headed mob, . . . he cares not, but, after the fashion of the globe, keeps himself rounded and compaet, too smooth for any blemish from without to settle upon him.
